that “converts significant amounts of mixed municipal waste into a US EPA recognized Solid Recovered Fuel and reduces landfill usage by up to 80 percent. The technology has been commercially deployed in Europe with 8 active facilities.”"},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"text","text":"“It’s the wave of the future,” Mayor Daniel Dwyer said."},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"text","text":"The city anticipates seeing an expansion of its tax base, about 24 jobs created and the restoration of the BASF site to productive use. Moore said this is an instance of a razed site being returned to useful industrial production."},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"text","text":"The plant will be designed to hold down odor, light and noise pollution, he said."},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"text","text":"The Planning Commission will name itself the lead agency for conducting the state environmental quality review required for the project. The commission meets at 6:30 p.m. Monday in City Hall."},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"text","text":"The proposed project fits into activities permitted in the industrial zoned area in the port area, Moore said. The project will require a special use variance."},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"text","text":"https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Rensselaer-sees-35-million-biotech-plant-as-12904167.php"},{"type":"hard_break"},{"type":"hard_break"}]}]},"source":"Times Union:  The wave of the future"}